{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> βροτός</b>, ὁ, <br /> poet. Noun, <b>mortal man</b>, opposed to ἀθάνατος or θεός, in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] usually <i>substantive</i>, οἷοι νῦν βροτοί εἰσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.304, +others; βροτὸς εἰς θεόν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 1196 (Lyric poetry); λόγος τις Ζῆνα μιχθῆναι βροτῷ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 295; θεοῦ δὲ πληγὴν οὐχ ὑπερπηδᾷ βροτός 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 961 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; βροτοί,opposed to νεκροί, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ant.” 850 (Lyric poetry); but β. ἀνήρ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.361; and so β. ἔθνος 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 10.28: as _feminine_, β. αὐδήεσσα 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.334; β. οὖσαν “Anthologia Graeca” 9.89 (1st c.AD: Philippus Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; but βροταί· γυναῖκες, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus (assuming variant): frequently in _genitive_ _plural_, after πολλοί 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 1.42, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 981, etc.; after τίς [prev. work] 437, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; βροτοί never takes the <i>Article</i> in Trag. and Comedy texts, except when an <i>adjective</i> or <i>pronoun</i> is added, τῶν πολυπόνων β. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 175 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἡμεῖς οἱ β. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 601, “Pax” 849, compare 5th c.BC: Sannyrio Comicus 1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οἱ ταλαίπωροι β. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 66 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; οἱ πάντες β. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 538.8.—Rare in Prose, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philos